overview_summary: None of the three profiled neighbors have a documented stance for or against development or clean energy, as no public statements or records could be found. All are private landowners with low public profiles, and none hold known positions of influence in the community. As a result, all three are classified with an **unknown** stance and **low** community influence. The adjacent landowners are primarily businesses invested in industrial development. These include a national grocery chain building a large distribution center, a data center company that bought land for future facilities, and a local construction supply firm expanding its operations. Most neighbors have recently acquired or developed property in the area, indicating generally pro-development stances and economic interests rather than organized opposition. The adjacent landowners include a municipal government and several private LLCs likely focused on land investment or development. The City of Peoria controls multiple nearby parcels and has a pro-growth stance, while the LLCs (e.g., a logistics developer and local land speculators) appear driven by financial interests. Key risks are potential opposition from the industrial developer guarding its expansion plans and opportunistic holds by speculators seeking windfalls. However, no obvious organized anti-development factions emerge—these neighbors primarily represent commercial interests or government stakeholders. The neighboring organizational landowners are a mix of a large energy infrastructure firm and small private LLCs with land holdings. Transwestern Pipeline Company, a major pipeline operator, is focused on protecting its right-of-way rather than local development. The other entities (Sharro LLC, DCMS Properties LLC, Num 1 Job LLC, JGJ Real Estate Experts LLC) appear to be land investors or small businesses with little public presence, likely motivated by property value and financial considerations. None shows evidence of significant community influence or outspoken stance, suggesting opposition (if any) would be driven by individual financial interests or safety concerns rather than organized community action. Among the adjacent landowners are two small construction companies and three property-holding LLCs. The contractors (Concrete Coring Co. and H & H Masonry) are long-established local businesses focused on operations, with moderate influence but no record of active opposition to development ([leadiq.com](https://leadiq.com/c/concrete-coring-company/5ecfdf3c8a998f161e9aa337/employee-directory?page=2#:~:text=Construction%20%20351)).
